President Trump tweeted that his "legal team will be holding a big press conference" at the Four Seasons in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on the morning of March 7. He later tweeted back that he would be meeting at the Four Seasons Total Landscaping. In response, the Four Seasons Hotel tweeted that the location had nothing to do with them.
The location where Trump's counsel, Rudy Giuliani and his team met was, after all, the parking lot of a landscaping company called Four Seasons Total Landscaping.
That morning, Trump repeated on Twitter his unsupported claim that his vote opening and other work in Pennsylvania was illegal. Twitter soon displayed a warning that he may be misleading people about how to participate in the election and other civic events. Twitter has frequently displayed similar warnings in Trump's tweets about casting votes.
White House officials said on Thursday that Trump was angry and dismayed that his aides and supporters were not backing and supporting him more on television and in the streets.
Trump said he has been in the White House, going back and forth between the Oval Office and the residence building, watching television and calling campaign offices around the country.
Several aides were absent from work on March 6 and the atmosphere inside the White House was "very grim" and somber, sources said.
Also that evening, it was revealed that Mark Meadows, 61, the president's chief of staff, had contracted the new coronavirus.
Although Trump has indicated to several senior advisers that he intends to continue filing lawsuits against the results of the vote opening, there is still no clear litigation strategy, according to administration officials.
One of the president's senior advisers revealed that Trump was "somewhere between muggy and positive" as of March 6. The source added that in 2016, Trump didn't think he could win at all.
There is no confirmed evidence of any coherent election fraud. The Trump campaign has offered no support for their claims.
Katia Andrus, a spokeswoman for the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights, which is sending an election watchdog to the United States, told BBC radio that there was no evidence of coherent illegal activity.

ドナルド・トランプ大統領が昨年の選挙で「何百万人もの」人々が不法投票したと主張し続ける中、大統領チームは戦略を話し合うために非公開の会合を開いている。


