Trump held a press conference at the White House at about 6:30 p.m. Eastern Time (8:30 a.m. EDT) on April 5. "If we count the legal votes, I win. If I count the illegal votes, the other side will try to steal the election," he said.
He also claimed that there have been "a lot of lawsuits because this (election) process is terribly unfair". However, most of the lawsuits have been filed by the Trump campaign.
Trump went on to say that he was "surprised that the mail-in ballot is so one-sided". So far, about 75 percent of the mail ballots are believed to be for Biden. Trump has long urged his supporters to vote at the polls, arguing that mail-in ballots are a source of fraud.
After repeating, without backing it up, that there is fraud in this election, Trump said, "Our goal is to protect the legitimacy of the election. We will not tolerate fraud in an attempt to steal an important election," he insisted. He indicated his intention to settle the case in court, saying, "The judges will make the final decision.
He then left the room without taking questions from reporters.
Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, the second most powerful Republican after Trump, released a statement on the morning of March 6. 'In our great country, this is how it should work. Every legitimate vote should be counted. Any votes submitted illegally should not be counted. All sides must be given the opportunity to watch the proceedings. And the courts are there to apply the law and resolve disputes," he expressed.
Several Republican officials have criticized Trump's comments. Senator Pat Toomey (R-Pennsylvania) told NBC that Trump's speech was "very painful to watch" and that "the president's claims of massive fraud and theft of the election and so on are completely unsupported. I am not aware that there was any massive fraud or anything like that.
Sen. Mitt Romney (Utah), the Republican nominee for the 2012 presidential election and a frequent critic of Mr. Trump, said after Mr. Biden's upset in Pennsylvania that "the president has called for a recount, called for an investigation into the alleged fraudulent votes where there is evidence, and exhausted every legal action You have the right to do this. It's part of the electoral process in this country. On the other hand, it is wrong to say that the elections were set up, corrupt, stolen, etc. Such statements hurt the goals of freedom in this country and around the world, undermine the institutions on which our republican government is based, and stir up destructive and dangerous passions uncontrollably," he said in his comments.
Ron Christie, a former staffer in the George W. Bush administration, told the BBC that it was not for the president to decide which votes were legal or illegal, and criticized the president for "once again missing an opportunity to behave like a president in this close election," in the Florida recount issue of the 2000 presidential election. Mr. Christie, who was in the Bush campaign at the time, said it was something that Mr. Bush and Al Gore had refrained from saying at the time to prevent tensions between their supporters from deteriorating.
Maryland Gov. Larry Hogan, a Republican, said, "There is no way to defend the president's comments tonight that undermine the democratic process in this country. America is counting its votes. We must respect the outcome, as we have always done. There is no election or person more important than democracy in this country," he tweeted.

ドナルド・トランプ米大統領は、民主党のライバルであるジョー・バイデン氏が、前副大統領に1票差で敗れたペンシルベニア州で選挙を盗もうとしていると非難している。

"合法票を数えれば私の勝ち。違法票を数えれば、相手側は選挙を盗もうとするだろう」と述べ、「最終的な判断は裁判官が下す」と法廷で決着をつける意向を示した
共和党関係者もトランプ氏の発言を批判している。

トランプ氏は、今回の選挙に不正があることを裏付けもなく繰り返した後、「我々の目標は選挙の正当性を守ることだ」と述べた。パット・トゥーミー上院議員（R・ペンシルベニア州）はNBCの取材に対し、トランプ氏の演説は「見ていて非常に痛々しいものだった」とし、「選挙の大規模な不正や盗用などの大統領の主張は全く裏付けがない」と述べた。バイデン氏はペンシルバニア州で「大統領は再集計を求め、証拠があるところでは不正票疑惑の調査を求め、あらゆる法的手段を尽くした」と動揺している。 あなたにはこれを行う権利があります。


